Rectangles are pretty messed up.  The app puts rectangles in the middle of land masses.  Rectangle courses should be made to be physically flyable and allow for enough time between rectangles, or a penalty for missing one other than ending the run.  Rectangles probably should not be overlaid on a scenery.  Also, there is no indication of the altitude of the rectangles,  which is bad because you  can't look around the way you can  a real cockpit; you have to actually pitch to try to find it.  Being able to replay a flight is cool, although that feature should be available for rectangles as well.  Perhaps it is just me, but in-flight refueling seems impossible.

replyContent:
From Version 5.8 you will find two controls mode: Simple and Full. Use "Full" controls level to access fine airbrake and flaps settings.

Set "calibrate on start" from the menu "Options"> "Settings". Then choose in page "calibration" that appears before the flight: "airplane controls" > simple or full (with airbrakes and flaps)

As much as I'd like to rate this higher, the choppy graphics make it almost unbearable. The responsiveness of controls and views is quite poor, and the lack of a rudder makes it highly unrealistic. Simply rolling left does not cause you to track to the left (in a real plane). The rudder must also be used in conjunction with the ailerons and elevators. Speeds achieved with the various aircrafts are way overstated, and resource usage is off the map. For a true flight simulation, get X-Plane.

About the head up display (HUD)  Attitude & Flight Path Indicator are 2 different things, with the new update the attitude bar is missing.  The attitude bar indicates the airplane's attitude—that is, the combination of its pitch and roll which Most of the time is a V shaped bar.  The bar with a circle in the center of it is called the flight path indicator. It represents where the plane is actually flying, rather than where it is pointed.  The application is missing the most important one, the attitude bar.
